22'''||[[Davoud Fanaei]]\n|-\n|colspan=3|'''Manager:'''\n|-\n|colspan=\"4\"|{{flagicon|BIH}} [[Miroslav Bla\u017eevi\u0107]]\n|}\n|valign=\"top\" width=\"50%\"|\n{| style=\"font-size: 90%\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" align=center\n|-\n!width=\"25\"| !!width=\"25\"|\n|-\n|GK ||'''1''' ||[[Shay Given]]\n|-\n|DF ||'''2''' ||[[Steve Finnan]]\n|-\n|DF ||'''3'''||[[Ian Harte]]\n|-\n|DF ||'''4''' ||[[Gary Breen]]\n|-\n|DF ||'''5''' ||[[Steve Staunton]]\n|-\n|MF ||'''6''' ||[[Mark Kinsella]]\n|-\n|MF ||'''7''' ||[[Jason McAteer]]|| || {{yel|84}}\n|-\n|MF ||'''8''' ||[[Matt Holland]]\n|-\n|MF ||'''11'''||[[Kevin Kilbane]] || ||{{suboff|85}}\n|-\n|FW ||'''9'''||[[David Connolly]]\n|-\n|FW ||'''10''' ||[[Robbie Keane]] || || {{yel|49}}  || ||{{suboff|75}}\n|-\n|colspan=3|'''Substitutions:'''\n|-\n|GK ||'''16'''||[[Alan Kelly Jr.]]\n|-\n|DF ||'''12'''||[[Gary Kelly (footballer, born 1974)|Gary Kelly]]|| ||{{subon|85}}\n|-\n|DF ||'''13''' ||[[Kenny Cunningham]]\n|-\n|FW ||'''17'''||[[Niall Quinn]]\n|-\n|MF ||'''14'''||[[Lee Carsley]]\n|-\n|FW ||'''18'''||[[Clinton Morrison]]|| ||{{subon|75}}\n|-\n|DF ||'''15'''||[[Andy O'Brien (footballer)|Andy O'Brien]]\n|-\n|colspan=3|'''Manager:'''\n|-\n|colspan=\"4\"|[[Mick McCarthy]]\n|}\n|}\n{| width=100% style=\"font-size: 90%\"\n| width=50% valign=top|\n'''OFFICIALS'''\n*Assistant referees:\n**[[Erick Mora]] ([[Costa Rican Football Federation|Costa Rica]])\n**[[Efrain Rodriguez]] ([[Costa Rican Football Federation|Costa Rica]])\n*Fourth official: [[Olger Mej\u00edas Ovares]] ([[Costa Rican Football Federation|Costa Rica]])\n| width=50% valign=top|\n'''MATCH RULES'''\n*90 minutes\n*30 minutes of [[Overtime (sports)#Association football|extra-time]] if necessary\n*Penalty shoot-out if scores still level:\n*3 (of 7) [[Substitute (football)|substitutions]] permitted\n|}\n\n==Aftermath==\nIreland qualified for the 2002 FIFA World Cup Finals in [[South Korea]] and [[Japan]], and were drawn into Group E with [[Germany national football team|Germany]], [[Cameroon national football team|Cameroon]] and [[Saudi Arabia national football team|Saudi Arabia]]. Ireland drew Cameroon and Germany with the same score 1\u20131 and in the final match they won 3\u20130 to Saudi Arabia so they qualified to the Round of 16 but they were eliminated to Spain with penalties (2-3) after finishing 1-1.\n\nIran failed to qualify for [[World Cup 2002]] after an aggregate defeat to the [[Republic of Ireland national football team|Republic of Ireland]], losing 2\u20130 in [[Dublin]] and winning 1\u20130 in [[Tehran]]. The elimination saw manager [[Miroslav Bla\u017eevi\u0107]] step down from the top spot to be replaced by his assistant [[Branko Ivankovi\u0107]], who stepped up from assistant coach.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{2002 FIFA World Cup qualification}}\n{{Republic of Ireland national football team matches}}\n{{Iran national football team matches}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:2002 FIFA World Cup qualification (UEFA-AFC play-off)}}\n[[Category:2001\u201302 in Republic of Ireland association football|FIFA]]\n[[Category:2001\u201302 in Iranian football|FIFA]]\n[[Category:2002 FIFA World Cup qualification|Play-off UEFA-AFC]]\n[[Category:FIFA World Cup qualification inter-confederation play-offs|2002]]\n[[Category:Republic of Ireland national football team matches]]\n[[Category:Iran national football team matches]]\n[[Category:Republic of Ireland at the 2002 FIFA World Cup|qual]]\n[[Category:November 2001 sports events in Europe]]\n[[Category:November 2001 sports events in Asia]]\n[[Category:2000s in Dublin (city)]]\n[[Category:21st century in Tehran]]\n[[Category:International sports competitions in Dublin (city)|Football]]\n[[Category:Sport in Tehran]]\n[[Category:International association football competitions hosted by the Republic of Ireland]]\n[[Category:International association football competitions hosted by Iran]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox football match\n| title                   = 2002 FIFA World Cup qualification<br>([[UEFA]]\u2013[[Asian Football Confederation|AFC]] play-off)\n| image                   =\n| event                   = [[2002 FIFA World Cup qualification]]\n| team1                   = [[Republic of Ireland national football team|Republic of Ireland]]\n| team1association        = {{flagicon|IRL|size=30px}}\n| team1score              = 2\n| team2                   = [[Iran national football team|Iran]]\n| team2association        = {{flagicon|IRN|size=30px}}\n| team2score              = 1\n| details                 = Republic of Ireland won 2\u20131 on aggregate\n| firstleg                = First leg\n| team1score1             = 2\n| team2score1             = 0\n| details1                =\n| date1                   = 10 November 2001\n| stadium1                = [[Lansdowne Road]]\n| city1                   = [[Dublin]]\n| referee1                = [[Ant\u00f4nio Pereira|Antonio Pereira da Silva]] ([[Brazilian Football Confederation|Brazil]])\n| attendance1             = 36,538\n| weather1                =\n| secondleg               = Second leg\n| team1score2             = 0\n| team2score2             = 1\n| details2                = \n| date2                   = 15 November 2001\n| stadium2                = [[Azadi Stadium]]\n| city2                   = [[Tehran]]\n| referee2                = [[William Mattus|William Mattus Vega]] ([[Costa Rican Football Federation|Costa Rica]])\n| attendance2             = 100,000\n| weather2                =\n}}\nThe '''[[2002 FIFA World Cup]] [[UEFA]]\u2013[[Asian Football Confederation|AFC]] qualification play-off''' was a [[Two-legged tie|two-legged]] home-and-away tie between a group runner-up of the [[2002 FIFA World Cup qualification (UEFA)|European qualifying tournament]], the [[Republic of Ireland national football team|Republic of Ireland]], and the winners of the [[2002 FIFA World Cup qualification (AFC)#Play-off|AFC play-off]], [[Iran national football team|Iran]]. The games were played on 10 November and 15 November 2001 in [[Dublin]] and [[Tehran]], respectively.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/archive/koreajapan2002/matches/preliminaries/index.html |title=2002 FIFA World Cup Korea/Japan - Qualifiers |website=FIFA.com |publisher=F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de Football Association |access-date=10 October 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\n{|  style=\"width:100%; text-align:center;\"\n|-  style=\"vertical-align:top; background:#9cf;\"\n!colspan=2 style=\"width:1*\"|Republic of Ireland\n!Round\n!colspan=2 style=\"width:1*\"|Iran\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" align=\"center\"|\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:175px;\"|Team\n!width=\"20\"|{{Tooltip| Pld | Played}}\n!width=\"20\"|{{Tooltip| W | Won}}\n!width=\"20\"|{{Tooltip| D | Drawn}}\n!width=\"20\"|{{Tooltip| L | Lost}}\n!width=\"20\"|{{Tooltip| GF | Goals for}}\n!width=\"20\"|{{Tooltip| GA | Goals against}}\n!width=\"20\"|{{Tooltip| GD | Goal difference}}\n!width=\"20\"|{{Tooltip| Pts | Points}}\n|- style=\"background:#ccffcc;\"\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{fb|POR}}\n|10||7||3||0||33||7||26||'''24'''\n|- style=\"background:#ffebad;\"\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{fb|IRL}}\n|10||7||3||0||23||5||18||'''24'''\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{fb|NED}}\n|10||6||2||2||30||9||21||'''20'''\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{fb|EST}}\n|10||2||2||6||10||26||-16||'''8'''\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{fb|CYP|1960}}\n|10||2||2||6||13||31||-18||'''8'''\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{fb|AND}}\n|10||0||0||10||5||36||-31||'''0'''\n|-\n|}\n| style=\"background:#c1e0ff;\"|Final standings\n| colspan=\"2\" align=\"center\"|\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:175px;\"|Team\n!width=\"20\"|{{Tooltip| Pld | Played}}\n!width=\"20\"|{{Tooltip| W | Won}}\n!width=\"20\"|{{Tooltip| D | Drawn}}\n!width=\"20\"|{{Tooltip| L | Lost}}\n!width=\"20\"|{{Tooltip| GF | Goals for}}\n!width=\"20\"|{{Tooltip| GA | Goals against}}\n!width=\"20\"|{{Tool